[CS304] Tutorial 9 - CI/CD tools
What is CI/CD?
CI (Continuous Integration) – automatically build and test every code change pushed to a shared
repository.
CD (Continuous Delivery / Deployment) – extend CI so the tested application is always ready to be
released (or even deployed automatically).
In this tutorial you will:
Set up a Jenkins Pipeline for a Maven project (Teedy)
Create a GitHub Actions workflow to build and publish artifacts
(Optional) Trigger Jenkins from GitHub Actions
Part I: Jenkins Pipeline
Install and run Jenkins
1. Download Jenkins Generic Java package (.war) from jenkins.io/download and save it to wherever
you want.
2. Open a terminal, navigate to the directory containing the  .war  file, and start Jenkins:
java -jar jenkins.war --httpPort=8080
If your Maven is installed in WSL, run this command inside the WSL terminal.
3. The terminal output will show an initial admin password. Copy this password – you’ll need it to
unlock Jenkins.
4. Open you browser and go to http://localhost:8080.
5. On the unlock page, the username is  admin . Paste the initial password you copied.
If you missed the password, you can still find it at
/home/<your-username>/.jenkins/secrets/initialAdminPassword .
6. Follow the setup wizard. Choose Install suggested plugins if you are new to Jenkins.
7. Install the Maven Integration plugin:
Click System Management:
Choose Plugins Management:
Go to Available Plugins tab, search for “Maven Integration”, select it, and click Install.
8. Restart Jenkins after installation.
Create a Jenkins Pipeline project
Now Let's use Jenkins to manage your Teedy project.
1. From the Jenkins dashboard, click New Item.
2. Enter a name for your project, select Pipeline.
3. In the project configuration, scroll to the Pipeline section.
Under Definition, choose Pipeline script from SCM.
Under SCM, select Git.
Enter your repository URL (the same Teedy repo you’re working on).
If your repository is private, you'll need to provide a GitHub personal access token. Refer to
How to use GitHub Personal Access Token in Jenkins.
4. Click Save to store the configuration.
Add a Jenkinsfile
Inside your Teedy repository, create a file named  Jenkinsfile  (no extension) at the root. This
declarative pipeline defines the entire build process.
pipeline {
    agent any
    stages {
        stage('Clean') {
            steps {
                sh 'mvn clean'
            }
        }
        stage('Compile') {
            steps {
                sh 'mvn compile'
            }
        }
        stage('Test') {
            steps {
                sh 'mvn test -Dmaven.test.failure.ignore=true'
            }
        }
        stage('PMD') {
            steps {
                sh 'mvn pmd:pmd'
            }
        }
        stage('JaCoCo') {
            steps {
                sh 'mvn jacoco:report'
            }
        }
        stage('Javadoc') {
            steps {
                sh 'mvn javadoc:javadoc'
            }
        }
        stage('Site') {
            steps {
                sh 'mvn site'
            }
        }
        stage('Package') {
            steps {
                sh 'mvn package -DskipTests'
            }
        }
    }
    post {
        always {
            archiveArtifacts artifacts: '**/target/site/**/*.*', fingerprint: true
            archiveArtifacts artifacts: '**/target/**/*.jar', fingerprint: true
            archiveArtifacts artifacts: '**/target/**/*.war', fingerprint: true
            junit '**/target/surefire-reports/*.xml'
        }
    }
}
Explanation of the pipeline:
Stages: Clean → Compile → Test → PMD → JaCoCo → Javadoc → Site → Package.
Stage Javadoc:this step invokes the Maven Javadoc Plugin to automatically generate API
documentation from Javadoc comments in your Java source code. The output is a set of
HTML pages that describe classes, methods, constructors, and fields.-- Why include Javadoc generation in CI?
Ensures documentation is always up-to-date with the latest source code.
Exposes documentation as a build artifact (site report) that can be reviewed or referenced
later.-- How to make  mvn javadoc:javadoc  work?
declare the  maven-javadoc-plugin  in Teedy's  pom.xml  ( <build>  and  <reporting> ) like
 jacoco .
 post { always { ... } } : Archives test results, site documentation, JAR and WAR files after
every build.
