Run the Pipeline
1. Go to your pipeline project in Jenkins and click Build Now.
2. Jenkins will pull the latest commit from your Git repository and execute the stages defined in the
Jenkinsfile sequentially.
3. Click on the build number (for example,  #5 ) view live progress.
4. After the build finishes, you can inspect:
Console Output – full build log.
Workspace – files checked out by Jenkins.
Pipeline Overview - A visual representation of all stages defined in the Jenkinsfile. Each
stage is color-coded (green for success, red for failure) and shows its execution duration. It
gives an at-a-glance summary of the build flow, and clicking any stage takes you directly to its
detailed console log.
Build Artifacts – archived JARs, WARs, and site documentation (HTML) available for
download.
Note: If archived HTML pages (like the Maven site) do not render correctly (missing
CSS/JS), this is due to Jenkins' security restrictions. See this workaround.
Part II: Github Actions
Create a workflow
1. In your GitHub repository, go to the Actions tab.
2. You can either:
choose a starter workflow (e.g., Publish Java Package with Gradle), or
click set up a workflow yourself to create a custom one.
3. Define the workflow file (e.g.,  .github/workflows/build.yml ) and paste the configuration below.
Teedy's Simplified CI Workflow
Teedy’s original workflow is at build-deploy.yml. For this tutorial we use only the build and publish
part (Docker is covered later).
name: Maven CI/CD
on:
  push:
    branches: [master]
    tags: [v*]
  workflow_dispatch:
jobs:
  build_and_publish:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v4
      - name: Set up JDK 11
        uses: actions/setup-java@v4
        with:
          java-version: "11"
          distribution: "temurin"
          cache: maven
      - name: Install test dependencies
        run: sudo apt-get update && sudo apt-get -y -q --no-install-recommends install ffmpeg me
      - name: Build with Maven
        run: mvn --batch-mode -Pprod clean install
      - name: Upload war artifact
        uses: actions/upload-artifact@v4
        with:
          name: docs-web-ci.war
          path: docs-web/target/docs*.war
Key steps explained:
Trigger: on push to  master  or new version tag, and manual dispatch.
Environment: uses  ubuntu-latest  with JDK 11 (Temurin distribution).
Build: runs Maven with the  prod  profile (production mode).
Artifact: uploads the generated WAR file so you can download it from the Actions run page.
Commit and View Results
1. Paste above contents to the  .yml  file, and click Commit changes...
2. Go to the Actions tab, you will see the workflow running.
3. After a successful run, you can download the  docs-web-ci.war  artifact from the workflow
summary.
